1
00:01:53,580 --> 00:01:57,175
Congressmen, we're now
flying over the heart of Berlin.

2
00:01:58,061 --> 00:02:00,051
Berlin.

3
00:02:01,821 --> 00:02:04,971
Over 75,000 tons of explosives
were dropped here.

4
00:02:05,020 --> 00:02:08,173
British Lancasters by night,
American Fortresses by day.

5
00:02:08,222 --> 00:02:12,009
I heard Russian artillery
had a little part in it too, if you don't mind.

6
00:02:12,061 --> 00:02:15,452
Sure they did and I wish
they'd pay us for all those cannons.

7
00:02:15,501 --> 00:02:19,290
Hey, quit juggling. Film like this
is good stuff around election time.

8
00:02:19,342 --> 00:02:20,933
The incumbent overseas.

9
00:02:20,981 --> 00:02:23,620
Pennecot, don't you want to see it?
Look at it.

10
00:02:23,661 --> 00:02:28,132
Like pack rats been gnawing at a hunk
of old mouldy Roquefort cheese.

11
00:02:28,181 --> 00:02:29,773
(Gags)

12
00:02:34,222 --> 00:02:37,533
Miss Frost? Congresswoman Frost?

13
00:02:37,583 --> 00:02:40,143
- Present.
- We're flying over Berlin.

14
00:02:42,743 --> 00:02:44,938
15 minutes ahead of schedule.

15
00:02:44,982 --> 00:02:47,338
Well, don't you want to see it?

16
00:02:47,383 --> 00:02:49,374
One thing at a time.

17
00:03:26,465 --> 00:03:30,254
You got quite a sight coming.
Looks like chicken innards at frying time.

18
00:03:30,306 --> 00:03:32,865
Considering the taxpayers' money
poured on it,

19
00:03:32,906 --> 00:03:35,293
I don't expect it to look like a lace Valentine.

20
00:03:39,386 --> 00:03:41,183
Golly.

21
00:03:46,226 --> 00:03:50,014
(Man) Well, that's rough doing.
That sure is rough doing.

22
00:03:54,347 --> 00:03:57,976
(2nd man) They ought to put in grass
and move in a herd of longhorn.

23
00:03:58,027 --> 00:04:01,463
Build up their industries.
Get those smokestacks belching again.

24
00:04:01,507 --> 00:04:04,658
- Not without organised labour.
- We got to feed the people.

25
00:04:04,707 --> 00:04:07,780
You can't keep a country
eating scraps out of garbage pails.

26
00:04:07,828 --> 00:04:10,978
I'm all for sending food,
only let 'em know where it's from.

27
00:04:11,027 --> 00:04:13,019
I object to dollar diplomacy.

28
00:04:13,068 --> 00:04:16,219
- But you don't mind sending food.
- There's a difference.

29
00:04:16,268 --> 00:04:18,828
If you give a hungry man bread,
that's democracy.

30
00:04:18,868 --> 00:04:21,701
If you leave the wrapper on, it's imperialism.

31
00:04:21,748 --> 00:04:25,343
Gentlemen, these are
very grave problems indeed

32
00:04:25,388 --> 00:04:28,541
but they don't happen to be
the problems of this committee.

33
00:04:28,589 --> 00:04:31,501
Perhaps I should remind you
why we were sent to Berlin,

34
00:04:31,549 --> 00:04:34,347
since our chairman,
Mr Pennecot of New Hampshire,

35
00:04:34,389 --> 00:04:38,506
has been indisposed ever since
we took off from Washington.

36
00:04:38,548 --> 00:04:42,667
We're here to investigate the morale
of American occupation troops,

37
00:04:42,709 --> 00:04:44,507
nothing else.

38
00:04:44,550 --> 00:04:47,939
12,000 of our boys are policing
that pest hole down below

39
00:04:47,989 --> 00:04:53,063
and according to reports, they are being
infected by a kind of moral malaria.

40
00:04:53,110 --> 00:04:57,740
It is our duty to their wives, their mothers,
their sisters, to find the facts.

41
00:04:57,790 --> 00:04:59,781
And if these reports are true,

42
00:04:59,830 --> 00:05:03,948
to fumigate that place with
all the insecticides at our disposal.

43
00:05:03,990 --> 00:05:07,870
If you'll pardon me,
we're approaching Tempelhof Airfield.

44
00:05:09,191 --> 00:05:12,342
(Man) Oh, God, if they haven't got
a reception out for us.

45
00:05:12,390 --> 00:05:14,188
(2nd man) A band and everything.

46
00:05:14,231 --> 00:05:16,426
(3rd man) They'll be glad to see home folks.

47
00:05:26,031 --> 00:05:30,867
Men, once more it is our honour and
privilege to welcome a visiting committee.

48
00:05:30,912 --> 00:05:35,270
Lately they seem to be coming
as regularly as the electric bill.

49
00:05:35,313 --> 00:05:37,668
This time it's not just VIPs.

50
00:05:37,713 --> 00:05:40,432
This time we're getting VIPIs.

51
00:05:40,473 --> 00:05:43,191
Very Important Persons Indeed.

52
00:05:43,232 --> 00:05:47,704
Some Congressional committee
to investigate our morale.

53
00:05:47,753 --> 00:05:52,223
Seems back home, they've got an idea
this here is one great big picnic,

54
00:05:52,272 --> 00:05:55,663
that all we do is swing in hammocks
with blonde Fräuleins,

55
00:05:55,713 --> 00:05:57,783
swap cigarettes for castles on the Rhine

56
00:05:57,833 --> 00:06:00,393
and soak our feet in sparkling Mosel.

57
00:06:00,433 --> 00:06:02,503
Well, let's not kid ourselves.

58
00:06:02,553 --> 00:06:05,272
Some of you do go
overboard once in a while.

59
00:06:05,313 --> 00:06:09,432
Maybe some of you are working too hard
to enlighten the civilian population

60
00:06:09,474 --> 00:06:12,194
and maybe some of you
PX millionaires have found out

61
00:06:12,234 --> 00:06:16,352
you can parlay a pack of cigarettes
into something more than 20 smokes.

62
00:06:16,394 --> 00:06:19,307
After all, this isn't a Boy Scout camp.

63
00:06:19,354 --> 00:06:21,151
We've got a tough job on our hands

64
00:06:21,194 --> 00:06:24,345
and, by and large,
I think we're handling it darn well.

65
00:06:24,394 --> 00:06:27,034
For my dough, we're on the ball.

66
00:06:27,075 --> 00:06:29,795
Most of us, anyway... most of the time.

67
00:06:29,836 --> 00:06:35,627
What they've got to realise is you can't pin
sergeant's stripes on an archangel.

68
00:06:35,676 --> 00:06:38,588
Now, this committee
is going to be here for five days.

69
00:06:38,636 --> 00:06:41,355
Let's give them as good
an impression as possible.

70
00:06:41,396 --> 00:06:44,115
Not pussyfooting
around with a phoney attitude.

71
00:06:44,157 --> 00:06:46,717
That's not fair to them or us.

72
00:06:46,757 --> 00:06:49,668
I'm counting on you men to behave, period.

73
00:06:51,036 --> 00:06:54,585
Morale. Maybe some day we can send
a little committee of our own

74
00:06:54,636 --> 00:06:56,991
to investigate morale in Washington, DC.

75
00:07:01,637 --> 00:07:05,755
Hey, look what I picked up
at the Brandenburg Gate.

76
00:07:07,157 --> 00:07:09,352
- How much?
- A dozen candy bars.

77
00:07:10,198 --> 00:07:12,392
They've still got some nine and a halfs.

78
00:07:12,437 --> 00:07:14,792
- I got no one to give them to.
- How about Trudy?

79
00:07:14,837 --> 00:07:18,432
I lost her. Russian sergeant came along
with a pound of rancid butter.

80
00:07:18,477 --> 00:07:21,629
- Those German dames are all alike.
- Speak for yourself.

81
00:07:21,678 --> 00:07:25,466
I wouldn't be afraid
of a Russian general with a ton of caviar.

82
00:07:26,398 --> 00:07:28,195
Nice toe.

83
00:07:30,518 --> 00:07:32,316
The best.

84
00:07:41,520 --> 00:07:43,714
We're here, Congressman.
Ready to unload?

85
00:07:46,079 --> 00:07:48,274
([Music:] Upbeat march)

86
00:07:54,038 --> 00:07:56,428
(Drill sergeant) Present... arms!

87
00:08:13,720 --> 00:08:16,110
- Hello, Colonel.
- Nice to see you, General.

88
00:08:16,161 --> 00:08:20,278
Mr Giffin from Texas, General Finney,
General McAndrew, Colonel Plummer.

89
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:22,516
- My pleasure.
- Mr Salvatore, from New York.

90
00:08:22,561 --> 00:08:25,997
- The Bronx.
- Nobody's going to think you're Wall Street.

91
00:08:26,041 --> 00:08:30,000
Mr Yandell, Congressman from Virginia.
Mr Kraus, Congressman from Illinois.

92
00:08:30,041 --> 00:08:33,636
Hold it, everybody.
Want to get some of this brass.

93
00:08:33,681 --> 00:08:35,479
Snappy little outfit you have.

94
00:08:35,522 --> 00:08:37,718
Thank you. I have to apologise for the band.

95
00:08:37,763 --> 00:08:40,754
- You should indeed.
- We're half strength today.

96
00:08:40,802 --> 00:08:43,362
- We generally have 40 pieces.
- That's terrible.

97
00:08:43,402 --> 00:08:47,316
We sent the others to the British sector
for a parade. It's Empire Day.

98
00:08:47,363 --> 00:08:51,834
What's terrible is I came hoping to find
an army taking its task with seriousness.

99
00:08:51,883 --> 00:08:54,238
Instead I find you have a 40-piece band.

100
00:08:54,283 --> 00:08:56,638
Perhaps you also have
some drum majorettes.

101
00:08:56,683 --> 00:08:58,197
- May I introduce...
- I know.

102
00:08:58,244 --> 00:09:01,235
General Finney, General McAndrew
and Colonel Plummer.

103
00:09:01,283 --> 00:09:05,071
It's in my data. I am Miss Frost,
Congresswoman from Iowa, 9th district.

104
00:09:05,123 --> 00:09:08,719
Delightful of Congress to send us
a lady representative for a change.

105
00:09:08,764 --> 00:09:09,879
Delightful.

106
00:09:09,924 --> 00:09:13,519
May I suggest here and now that
we dispense with all the soft soap.

107
00:09:13,563 --> 00:09:16,715
As committee chairman,
permit me to bring you greetings

108
00:09:16,764 --> 00:09:19,677
from the people
of the United States of America.

109
00:09:19,725 --> 00:09:24,560
This genial reception augurs well
for the success of our mission.

110
00:09:24,605 --> 00:09:29,200
I sincerely hope so. And now let us proceed
to a luncheon we have prepared for you.

111
00:09:29,244 --> 00:09:33,875
A very simple luncheon. Powdered egg
omelette, probably, and a little Spam.

112
00:09:40,846 --> 00:09:43,201
- Can I carry that for you?
- No, thank you.

113
00:09:43,246 --> 00:09:46,841
I undertook to deliver it in person
to a Captain John Pringle,

114
00:09:46,886 --> 00:09:49,242
stationed somewhere in Berlin, G2 Section.

115
00:09:49,286 --> 00:09:52,278
- Could you tell me how to go about it?
- I could try.

116
00:09:52,326 --> 00:09:55,636
Through army channels?
All I have is five days.

117
00:09:55,686 --> 00:09:56,756
Captain Pringle!

118
00:09:58,167 --> 00:09:59,964
Captain Pringle!

119
00:10:03,887 --> 00:10:05,638
Captain Pringle reporting, sir.

120
00:10:05,686 --> 00:10:08,405
Congresswoman Frost,
this is Captain Pringle.

121
00:10:08,446 --> 00:10:11,837
Thank you. This is for you,
Captain Pringle. Happy birthday.

122
00:10:11,887 --> 00:10:15,323
Or happy birthday yesterday.
I thought I could deliver it on time

123
00:10:15,367 --> 00:10:18,518
but we were held up
in Newfoundland for 16 hours - fog.

124
00:10:18,567 --> 00:10:21,923
- You brought this from America?
- Murdoch, Iowa.

125
00:10:21,967 --> 00:10:24,162
Well, how is good old Iowa?

126
00:10:24,207 --> 00:10:26,198
62°% Republican, thank you.

127
00:10:26,248 --> 00:10:30,639
I was entrusted with this by a constituent,
or rather, his daughter.

128
00:10:30,688 --> 00:10:33,248
I hope it's still in one piece. Open it.

129
00:10:33,288 --> 00:10:35,085
Be glad.

130
00:10:44,049 --> 00:10:46,609
Well, what do you know? Little Dusty.

131
00:10:48,850 --> 00:10:50,646
It's a beauty.

132
00:10:50,689 --> 00:10:52,681
I didn't know it was so personal.

133
00:10:52,729 --> 00:10:57,122
Her name is really Pauline Rose
but we call her Dusty. Some joke.

134
00:10:57,170 --> 00:11:00,764
- How long since you've seen her?
- Dusty? Four years.

135
00:11:00,810 --> 00:11:04,246
Don't these boys ever get home?
Can't they be given a short leave?

136
00:11:04,290 --> 00:11:07,202
- Certainly, if it's accrued.
- I don't want any leave.

137
00:11:07,250 --> 00:11:10,242
- You don't?
- Oh, of course I do. Dying to.

138
00:11:10,290 --> 00:11:13,248
We're all homesick
but personal feelings don't matter.

139
00:11:13,290 --> 00:11:15,281
There's unfinished business here.

140
00:11:15,330 --> 00:11:18,482
Now that we've won the war,
we mustn't lose the peace.

141
00:11:18,531 --> 00:11:22,080
I hate to think of anybody
sitting in his lonely barracks

142
00:11:22,131 --> 00:11:23,928
with a birthday cake on his knees.

143
00:11:23,970 --> 00:11:27,122
I won't have the cake on my knees.
I won't be alone.

144
00:11:28,131 --> 00:11:30,486
There'll be my buddies. I'll call them in.

145
00:11:30,531 --> 00:11:33,682
We'll open up a case of root beer,
light the candles,

146
00:11:33,731 --> 00:11:35,847
then Frankovitch and his ukulele.

147
00:11:35,891 --> 00:11:40,010
Some old songs.
Why, it'll be like back home... almost.

148
00:11:40,051 --> 00:11:41,805
Good to hear you talk like that.

149
00:11:41,852 --> 00:11:43,921
General Finney wants you to go in his car.

150
00:11:43,972 --> 00:11:45,372
I'll be right with you.

151
00:11:45,412 --> 00:11:49,963
If you're a sample of the spirit
prevailing in Berlin, I feel better already.

152
00:11:50,012 --> 00:11:52,368
- I'm a sample, all right.
- Goodbye.

153
00:11:57,452 --> 00:12:00,092
You're losing something, Captain Pringle.

154
00:12:01,013 --> 00:12:02,605
My handkerchief.

155
00:12:02,653 --> 00:12:05,009
You blow your nose in nylon nowadays?

156
00:12:07,494 --> 00:12:11,089
What do you know? There must have
been a mistake at the laundry.

157
00:12:11,135 --> 00:12:14,729
We got a crazy old laundress.
You know what happened to Frankovitch?

158
00:12:14,774 --> 00:12:18,288
He sent out his shorts and got back a girdle.
(Laughs)

159
00:12:19,334 --> 00:12:21,210
(Groans)

160
00:12:37,095 --> 00:12:39,085
Ask her how much.

161
00:12:39,134 --> 00:12:43,765
(Speaking German)

162
00:12:43,815 --> 00:12:45,807
800 cigarettes, or coffee.

163
00:12:46,775 --> 00:12:49,688
(Speaking German)

164
00:13:06,497 --> 00:13:10,284
No. This watch gold. Gold for teeth.

165
00:13:10,337 --> 00:13:12,532
- A watch from steel.
- How's this?

166
00:13:12,577 --> 00:13:15,137
No, this silver. Want steel.

167
00:13:15,177 --> 00:13:16,975
You want steel.

168
00:13:17,018 --> 00:13:21,134
No, want round watch, very big, nice face.

169
00:13:21,176 --> 00:13:24,965
You're tough. All right,
let's look in the other drawer.

170
00:13:26,857 --> 00:13:30,373
(Cackles) Mickey Mouse! Mickey Mouse!

171
00:13:30,418 --> 00:13:32,408
- How much?
- $700.

172
00:13:33,418 --> 00:13:36,728
- You got three like this watch, maybe?
- We'll see.

173
00:13:45,698 --> 00:13:49,977
Herr Captain, buy porcelain?
Little Cupid to take for wife?

174
00:13:50,019 --> 00:13:53,011
Never mind the knick-knacks.
How much for the mattress?

175
00:13:53,059 --> 00:13:55,856
- Why you want the mattress?
- I'm sleepy.

176
00:13:55,898 --> 00:13:59,176
- How much for the mattress?
- (Speaking German)

177
00:14:01,100 --> 00:14:03,294
What do you mean, "nein, nein, no"?

178
00:14:03,339 --> 00:14:05,296
Look what you can get for it.

179
00:14:05,340 --> 00:14:08,218
(Speaking German)

180
00:14:09,741 --> 00:14:12,891
12 eggs in it and look at
the writing on it and the candles.

181
00:14:12,940 --> 00:14:16,331
The candles alone are worth the mattress.
Get lost.

182
00:14:16,380 --> 00:14:18,451
(All speaking German)

183
00:15:38,505 --> 00:15:40,495
(Brakes squeal)

184
00:15:40,544 --> 00:15:42,536
(Honks horn)

185
00:16:11,266 --> 00:16:13,258
Yoo-hoo!

186
00:16:14,228 --> 00:16:16,980
Erika! Erika!

187
00:16:27,388 --> 00:16:29,379
(Whistling cheerfully)

188
00:16:32,749 --> 00:16:34,704
(Speaks German)

189
00:16:35,828 --> 00:16:38,388
Sit down, Johnny.

190
00:16:43,188 --> 00:16:45,179
Go away, Johnny, sit down.

191
00:17:03,709 --> 00:17:05,301
Johnny.

192
00:17:05,349 --> 00:17:07,705
Johnny, what are you doing?

193
00:17:07,750 --> 00:17:10,786
- I'm wiping my face.
- You're hurting me, Johnny.

194
00:17:10,829 --> 00:17:13,981
You're always hurting me.
Why are you so mean to me?

195
00:17:14,030 --> 00:17:17,227
I worry about you. I scrounge around,
I bring you presents

196
00:17:17,270 --> 00:17:18,908
and you tell me I'm mean to you.

197
00:17:18,950 --> 00:17:22,739
You brought me a present? Where is it?
Where have you got it?

198
00:17:22,791 --> 00:17:24,827
Ohh...

199
00:17:24,870 --> 00:17:28,989
Johnny, they're so sheer. So beautiful.

200
00:17:29,031 --> 00:17:32,182
52 gauge. So I'm mean to you?

201
00:17:32,231 --> 00:17:35,382
- No, you're good to me.
- You bet I am.

202
00:17:35,431 --> 00:17:39,550
You don't know how good. I bought
you another present. You're not gonna get it.

203
00:17:39,592 --> 00:17:42,741
Another one? Where have you got it?
Where is it, Johnny?

204
00:17:42,790 --> 00:17:45,624
- Keep away.
- Is it here? Tell me...

205
00:17:46,912 --> 00:17:51,143
Johnny... (Speaks German)

206
00:17:51,191 --> 00:17:53,910
- Where did you get it?
- A friend of mine baked it.

207
00:17:53,951 --> 00:17:57,740
Only you're not going to get it. Why
should I care whether you sleep or not?

208
00:17:57,793 --> 00:18:01,671
Johnny, for 15 years
we haven't slept in Germany.

209
00:18:01,712 --> 00:18:05,102
First it was Hitler screaming on the radio,
then the war of nerves,

210
00:18:05,152 --> 00:18:07,347
then the victory celebrations,

211
00:18:07,392 --> 00:18:09,384
then the bombing.

212
00:18:09,433 --> 00:18:11,424
All the furniture burnt.

213
00:18:11,473 --> 00:18:13,270
See?

214
00:18:13,313 --> 00:18:15,269
(Springs crash and boing)

215
00:18:15,313 --> 00:18:18,623
That one I hate worst.
Give me that mattress, Johnny.

216
00:18:18,673 --> 00:18:20,664
No mattress will help you sleep.

217
00:18:20,713 --> 00:18:23,102
What you Germans need
is a better conscience.

218
00:18:23,153 --> 00:18:24,951
I have a good conscience.

219
00:18:24,994 --> 00:18:28,145
I have a new Führer now... you.

220
00:18:28,194 --> 00:18:29,468
Heil, Johnny.

221
00:18:29,514 --> 00:18:32,153
You heil me once more
and I'll knock your teeth in.

222
00:18:32,194 --> 00:18:33,991
You'll bruise your lips.

223
00:18:34,035 --> 00:18:37,186
Why don't I choke you a little?
Break you in two?

224
00:18:37,995 --> 00:18:40,714
Build a fire under you, you blonde witch.

225
00:18:40,755 --> 00:18:42,188
(Knock at door)

226
00:18:42,236 --> 00:18:43,827
Who's that?

227
00:18:43,875 --> 00:18:45,866
With my luck, it's Eisenhower.

228
00:18:54,755 --> 00:18:56,746
- Yes.
- Your name Schlütow?

229
00:18:56,795 --> 00:18:59,515
- I beg your pardon.
- Is your name Erika Schlütow?

230
00:18:59,555 --> 00:19:01,546
- No.
- You live here, don't you?

231
00:19:01,595 --> 00:19:02,994
Yes, I live here.

232
00:19:03,035 --> 00:19:05,834
You the dame that sings
at the Lorelei nightclub?

233
00:19:05,876 --> 00:19:09,471
- Yes, I sing there.
- And your name's not Erika Schlütow?

234
00:19:10,515 --> 00:19:13,155
My name is Erika von Schlütow.

235
00:19:13,196 --> 00:19:15,187
- A von?
- She's a von.

236
00:19:15,236 --> 00:19:18,035
