([Music:] Singing in German)

1479
01:44:40,184 --> 01:44:42,746
([Music:] Singing in French)

1480
01:44:49,424 --> 01:44:51,896
([Music:] Singing in Russian)

1481
01:44:58,148 --> 01:45:00,866
(Cheering and applause)

1482
01:45:03,068 --> 01:45:05,708
(Gunshots, screaming)

1483
01:45:09,590 --> 01:45:13,784
So we followed her all day
until the five o'clock shadow showed.

1484
01:45:13,826 --> 01:45:16,466
- Sure enough, she was Hermann.
- Well, doggone.

1485
01:45:16,508 --> 01:45:18,499
You sure spin some tall tales.

1486
01:45:18,547 --> 01:45:21,697
Yeah, well, how about this?
Hans Otto Birgel.

1487
01:45:21,751 --> 01:45:24,103
Big Gestapo man hiding out underground.

1488
01:45:24,151 --> 01:45:28,267
The only lead we have is that
he's still crazy about a former lady friend,

1489
01:45:28,309 --> 01:45:31,189
a nightclub singer
somewhere in the American sector.

1490
01:45:32,389 --> 01:45:35,983
Herr Birgel suspects she's two-timing him
so he crawls out of his hole.

1491
01:45:36,031 --> 01:45:38,149
Only he doesn't crawl fast enough.

1492
01:45:38,191 --> 01:45:41,341
So we play it up a little
with the help of an American officer.

1493
01:45:41,389 --> 01:45:43,189
A captain, to be exact.

1494
01:45:43,231 --> 01:45:46,669
Make a fancy story in
a Sunday supplement someday.

1495
01:45:46,711 --> 01:45:49,987
- The Love Commando.
- (Woman) Ha.

1496
01:45:50,029 --> 01:45:53,821
Here's their angle. The Captain
isn't very keen for the assignment,

1497
01:45:53,875 --> 01:45:57,025
having fallen for
somebody else in the meantime.

1498
01:45:57,073 --> 01:46:00,193
You know how they cook it up
with a lot of marshmallow on top.

1499
01:46:00,235 --> 01:46:03,385
Then the story of how
they got the poison into Göring's cell.

1500
01:46:03,433 --> 01:46:06,229
- (Whistles blowing)
- There were two scrub women...

1501
01:46:08,155 --> 01:46:12,145
Sorry, sir. The car has to pull in.
Keeping the street open for the ambulance.

1502
01:46:12,193 --> 01:46:14,389
- What's up?
- Trouble at the Lorelei.

1503
01:46:14,437 --> 01:46:17,629
- Birgel showed up. There was shooting.
- (Plummer) Who got it?

1504
01:46:17,677 --> 01:46:20,586
- I don't know, sir.
- Excuse me, gentlemen.

1505
01:46:20,634 --> 01:46:23,274
Perhaps you'd want
to come along, Miss Frost.

1506
01:46:26,352 --> 01:46:27,582
Hey!

1507
01:46:27,636 --> 01:46:30,468
([Music:] Singing drunkenly in Russian)

1508
01:47:16,518 --> 01:47:20,117
Mm-hm. Two plugs right through the kisser.

1509
01:47:20,921 --> 01:47:21,989
No.

1510
01:47:23,759 --> 01:47:27,149
- It was an ugly kisser anyway.
- It was not.

1511
01:47:27,203 --> 01:47:30,191
He was no good
and he's dead and it's OK by me.

1512
01:47:30,239 --> 01:47:31,721
Ohh...

1513
01:47:31,763 --> 01:47:33,719
No sense of humour.

1514
01:47:33,761 --> 01:47:35,753
Take care of her, lover boy.

1515
01:47:41,003 --> 01:47:42,995
(Humming mournfully)

1516
01:47:44,201 --> 01:47:46,397
- All right, clean up the mess.
- Yes, sir.

1517
01:47:46,445 --> 01:47:50,915
Find him a slab before the Russkies
start tossing him up to the ceiling.

1518
01:47:54,923 --> 01:47:56,723
Go on home!

1519
01:47:56,765 --> 01:47:59,405
Come on, break it up, let's go. All right.

1520
01:47:59,447 --> 01:48:01,433
(Humming stops)

1521
01:48:03,005 --> 01:48:04,595
Where are you taking me?

1522
01:48:04,643 --> 01:48:08,435
Looks like you've got a date
with five million von bricks.

1523
01:48:08,483 --> 01:48:10,601
I have a paper saying I'm on the white list.

1524
01:48:10,643 --> 01:48:12,635
We know how you got it and it wasn't,

1525
01:48:12,683 --> 01:48:15,599
if you'll pardon
the non-Aryan expression, kosher.

1526
01:48:15,647 --> 01:48:17,765
You do not understand. There's a mix-up.

1527
01:48:17,807 --> 01:48:20,716
Yeah. We just sent part of it
off to the morgue.

1528
01:48:20,764 --> 01:48:23,722
- Just ask Captain Pringle.
- Forget Captain Pringle.

1529
01:48:23,764 --> 01:48:28,240
How could I ever forget him?
He's so nice. I will miss him terribly.

1530
01:48:28,288 --> 01:48:30,280
- Please tell him.
- No soap.

1531
01:48:30,328 --> 01:48:32,758
And no chocolate, no cigarettes.

1532
01:48:32,806 --> 01:48:34,762
Tough.

1533
01:48:35,848 --> 01:48:40,240
Tell me, Colonel, are you
that wonderful Colonel Plummer?

1534
01:48:40,288 --> 01:48:44,602
That's me,
only most of the time they call me delicious.

1535
01:48:44,650 --> 01:48:48,724
Colonel, if I could come to your office
tomorrow sometime,

1536
01:48:48,766 --> 01:48:50,644
when you're not too busy.

1537
01:48:50,686 --> 01:48:54,478
Miss von Schlütow,
I've become a grandfather today.

1538
01:48:54,532 --> 01:48:56,284
Let's not be silly.

1539
01:48:57,052 --> 01:48:59,038
She's all yours.

1540
01:48:59,092 --> 01:49:01,732
Can they take me
by my apartment so I can change?

1541
01:49:01,768 --> 01:49:05,206
- I guess so.
- Come on, boys.

1542
01:49:06,490 --> 01:49:08,482
Has it stopped raining?

1543
01:49:08,530 --> 01:49:12,526
If there are any puddles,
you'll carry me, won't you, boys?

1544
01:49:21,729 --> 01:49:23,925
You two, watch out for those two.

1545
01:49:23,973 --> 01:49:25,929
(Both) Yes, sir.

1546
01:49:31,371 --> 01:49:34,521
- And you watch out for them.
- That ought to do it.

1547
01:49:44,133 --> 01:49:47,049
He said there were two plugs in your kisser.

1548
01:49:47,097 --> 01:49:50,247
There ought to be.
I'm sorry about everything.

1549
01:49:50,295 --> 01:49:52,935
- Except the time with you.
- Take that away.

1550
01:49:52,977 --> 01:49:56,853
It's true. With all the headaches ahead,
you'll be my aspirin.

1551
01:49:56,895 --> 01:49:59,091
That's nice, but what about my headache?

1552
01:49:59,133 --> 01:50:01,089
You're on your way back home.

1553
01:50:01,137 --> 01:50:04,731
You'll be all right by the time
you fasten your seat belt.

1554
01:50:04,773 --> 01:50:06,735
I love you, John.

1555
01:50:08,337 --> 01:50:11,727
No, you don't. I'm just a hit-and-run boy.

1556
01:50:11,775 --> 01:50:14,769
The kind of guy you need
is somebody to marry.

1557
01:50:14,817 --> 01:50:16,407
Well?

1558
01:50:16,455 --> 01:50:19,293
Oh, no. I'm not somebody anybody marries.

1559
01:50:20,378 --> 01:50:26,168
You need somebody respectable,
a senator, a Supreme Court judge,

1560
01:50:26,216 --> 01:50:30,098
maybe... somebody from
the Smithsonian Institute.

1561
01:50:30,140 --> 01:50:31,730
I know who I want.

1562
01:50:31,778 --> 01:50:34,418
Not me, I'm a heel, a certified heel.

1563
01:50:34,460 --> 01:50:37,016
I got documents to prove it.

1564
01:50:37,058 --> 01:50:39,254
Listen...

1565
01:50:39,296 --> 01:50:43,292
"Listen, my children, and you shall hear
of the midnight ride of Paul Revere

1566
01:50:43,340 --> 01:50:47,492
"On the 18th of April in '75, hardly a man
is now alive who remembers..."

1567
01:50:47,540 --> 01:50:49,532
(Glass smashing)

1568
01:50:50,180 --> 01:50:51,452
Oh...

1569
01:51:02,553 --> 01:51:08,253
Adaptation by Ventisette


